Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt: To Seal Victim/Witness Identification Key signed by Judge Bugenhagen Jr. on October 31, 2022

If DNA sample has not been taken from the defendant, the Court orders sample to be taken; and it may be expunged under 165.77(4) Wis. Statutes. Defendant to comply with I.D. Processing. Defendant to have no contact with Victim A/Victim B/Witness A/co-defendant/Corey S. listed in the Criminal Complaint/Victim Identification Key. Defendant is not to share, reproduce or distribute any personal and/or identifying information about the crime victim(s), except to their attorney. Defendant is not to possess any dangerous weapons/firearms/knives.

2:06 PM Defendant Johnyae Q Harris in court, in custody.  Attorney Amanda Marie Nimmer in court for Johnyae Q Harris. District Attorney's Office Law Intern appeared for the State of Wisconsin by Jack Rieder. Attorney Nimmer appears as friend of the court. Defendant is not eligible for State Public Defender representation. Defense acknowledges receipt of complaint and waives reading of complaint. Service admitted/advised of charges and potential penalties. Court advises of right to an attorney. Court notes that CCAP lists Count 4 as a Class D Felony but it is actually a Class H Felony. The Court will set this matter back for status of counsel. Court tolled time limits for preliminary hearing.
Hearing scheduled for November 17, 2022 at 10:00 am.
